Subject: New Circular 04/2024: RELIEF MEASURES TO ASSIST THE AFFECTED SMALL AND MEDIUM ENTERPRISES

Dear Tharindu Perera,

A new circular has been published.

Summary:
Sri Lanka Banks’ Association (Guarantee) Ltd. (SLBA) has agreed that the relief measures in paragraph 1 below will be provided by the licensed commercial banks and licensed specialised banks. Relief measures will apply only to the credit facilities of SME borrowers of licensed banks that meet the following criteria and, in this regard, licensed banks will engage with the eligible borrowers. CENTRAL BANK of SRI LANKA 19 December 2024 CIRCULAR No. 04 of 2024 13 1.4 (bo) | Commencing of repayment of the rescheduled loans by eligible SMe borrowers where an aggregate capital outstanding of credit facilities as at 15.12.2024 is below Rs. 25 Mn, not later than 31.03.2025. 1.2. Reschedulement of impaired loans with eligible SME. borrowers identified in paragraph1.1 above, considering the repayment capacity of the borrower and. submission of an acceptable business revival plan, as given below. (a) Entering into rescheduler agreements with eligibleSME borrowers. (b) SMEs that commenced discussions on business revival with the Business Revival Units of the respective banks by 31. 03.20 25, subject to submission of all necessary documents. (c) Commencing. of repayment by SMEs where aggregate capital outlay of credit. facilities is between Rs.25 Mn - Rs.50 Mn. (d) Committing of repayment to the SME borrower where the aggregate capital. outstanding of. credit facilities is below £1,000, and the repayment date is between 30.09.20 and 30.06. 2025.

The Central Bank of Sri Lanka has waived off the unpaid interest (excluding capitalised interest) applicable to the period between 01.04.2019 and 15.12.2024 on the credit facilities of eligible SME borrowers. Licensed banks may consider further reliefs, including granting of working capital facilities to eligible borrowers subject to repayment capacity and submission of credible business revival plans, on a case-by-case basis. The Circular was issued on 19 December 2024 and comes into force on 1 January 2024. The circular was issued by Dr. P Nandalal Weerasinghe, Chairman of the Governing Board and Governor of the Central Bank. It was also issued by the Sri Lankan government and is available online at www.sri-lanka.gov. Sri Lanka is a member of the Asian Development Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF). The Central Bank is the largest lender of credit to the Sri Lanka economy. It is also the largest bank in the island nation, with a market value of over Rs. 1.2 trillion. It has a market share of more than 40%. It is one of the largest banks in Sri Lanka. It also has the largest market share in the world, with more than 80% of its market share coming from outside the country. The central bank is the biggest lender in the country, followed by Sri Lanka’s second largest bank, Sri Lanka Lanka Lanka Bank. Its market share is less than 10%. It has the highest market share among all banks in the nation, and the lowest market share amongst Sri Lankans. The number of licensed banks is more than 30.

